<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">he dispatched a Mandane and made his escape with the Scalp.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">About noon we came opposite the upper village where we found M<sup>r</sup> Chaboillez and M<sup>r</sup> M<sup>c</sup>Kenzie waiting our arrival.  The <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Borgne</span> with two of his wives were there also with fresh meat of which a meal was prepared for us &#8212; but which from the customary mode of cooking we could scarcely <span class="AddHand-author">taste</span>.  The women were however very troublesome fancying and wishing for all we had remaining of our things.  This hastened our departure<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Borgne</span> in bidding us adieu advised us to be upon our guard &#8212; as the season was arrived when the enemy frequented these parts<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Our party consisted of ten men and we had twenty five horses &#8212; but we were short of arms and ammunition for which great reason greater circumspection in our proceedings was required<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  We soon came to the heights of Snake lodge and encampted upon the upper part of <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Bourbeuse</span> river.  A shorter route than the one we had taken, but more dangerous on account of the enemy.  He we found <span style="text-decoration:underline;">poires</span> in great abundance &#8212; the branches were so loaded that the bushes yielded to the weight of their burdens.  I never saw such a quantity in any</p>
<p style="text-align:right;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">part</span></p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[79]</span></p>

